Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

The data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb) such as:

1) id: The unique ID of the movie.
2) imdb_id: The IMDB ID of the movie.
3) popularity: The Popularity Score of the movie by TMDB.
4) budget: The budget of the movie in dollars at its time of production.
5) revenue: The total revenue of the movie in dollars after its release.
6) original_title: The original title of the movie.
7) cast: The names of the actors participated in the movie, contains multiple separated values.
8) homepage: The official homepage of the move.
9) director: The name of the movie director.
10) tagline: The tagline of the movie.
11) keywords: The keywords by which the movie can be found.
12) overview: A brief summary of the movie.
13) runtime: The runtime of the movie in minutes.
14) genres: All the genres associated with the movie, contains multiple separated values.
15) production_companies: Production companies involved with the movie production, contains multiple separated values.
16) release_date: The release date of the movie.
17) vote_count: The number of votes by users, as counted by TMDB.
18) vote_average: The average rating of the movie out of 10.
19) release_year: The release year of the movie.
20) budget_adj: The budget of the movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.
21) revenue_adj: The total revenue of the movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

Here are some general questions that will be discussed along with the Analysis,

  • Which genres are most popular from year to year?
  • Which year has the most produced movies? and What genres are the most produced of all time?
  • How the average movies runtime changed over the years?
  • How is the film making production changing over the years?
  • What are the movies with the highest Budget, Revenue and Profit?

However, The Analysis will be focusing on the properties that are associated with movies with the highest revenues, the following topics will be discussed as well:

  • What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?
  • What is the effect of the following on the movie revenues?

    Release Date
    Production Company
    Director
    Cast
    Genres
    Budget
    Rating
    Popularity
    Runtime

Q1: Which genres are most popular from year to year?¶

In [30]:
# define a new function 'Split_Values'
def Split_Values(df, *cols):
    '''
    Split the values separated by ('|') in a column and Create a new DataFrame.
    Args:
        df - Pandas DataFrame containing the data.
        (str) *cols - All columns needed to construct the new DataFrame.
                (Note that the first value shall be the column to be splitted)
    Returns:
        df_split - DataFrame with the splitted values.
    '''
    split_cols=['id']
    split_cols.extend(cols)
    df_split = df.groupby(split_cols).count().reset_index()
    df_split[cols[0]] = df_split[cols[0]].str.split('|')
    df_split = df_split.explode(cols[0])
    return df_split

# Plotting genres which are popular in each year
fig, axs = plt.subplots(19, 3, figsize=(15, 73))
fig.tight_layout(h_pad= 4, w_pad= 7)
i=0
j=0
for year in sorted(df_pop_genre.release_year.unique()):
    pop = df_pop_genre[df_pop_genre.release_year == year].groupby('genres')['popularity'].sum().sort_values()
    axs[i,j].barh(width= pop.values, y= pop.index)
    axs[i,j].set_title('Popular Genres in {}'.format(year))
    axs[i,j].set_xlabel('Popularity')
    axs[i,j].set_ylabel('Genres')
    j+=1
    if j%3==0:
        i+=1
        j=0
plt.show()

Conclusions¶

Finally, reaching the end of the analysis, we can now summarize our findings and the results that have been concluded in relation to the question(s) provided at the beginning of the analysis in the following points:

Q1: Which genres are most popular from year to year?

  • Popularity of different genres is increasing over time in general, However, the top popular genres for each year are nearly the same; people tend to prefer Drama, Comedy, Action, Thriller, and Adventure.
  • Drama with total popularity of 2815 is the most popular genre of all time followed by Comedy, Action and Thriller with total popularity of 2247, 2208 and 2155 respectively.

Q2: What year has the most produced movies? and What genres are the most produced of all time?

  • Different Movies production is increasing over time in general, However, the most produced movies in total was in 2014 with a total of 1470 movies! which averages a whopping 4 movies per day!, followed by 2015, 2013 and 2009 with a total of 1386, 1383, 1358 movies respectively.
  • Drama with a total of 4760 movies is the most produced genre of all time followed by Comedy, Thriller and Action with a total of 3793, 2907 and 2384 movies respectively.

Q3: How does the movies runtime change over the years?

  • The average movie runtime is generally decreasing over the years.
  • We can see that we have the lowest average movie runtime in the recent 5 years starting from 2010 averaging about 97 minutes only.

    Part of the reason we could be seeing shorter movies is that studios are trying to boost ticket sales. “The old conventional wisdom about shorter movies is that you can have more showings in a day” as said by Paul Dergarabedian, Senior Media Analyst at comScore.

Q4: How is the film making industry growing over the years?

  • The film production industry is generally growing over the years in both aspects; movies budgets and revenues.
  • We can see that the total profits is increasing massively (Almost tripled!) in the recent 15 years starting from 2000 at which the total profits were about 17 Billions Dollars reaching about 50 Billions Dollars in 2015!.

Q5: What are the movies with the highest Budget, Revenue and Profit?

  • The top spending movie is The Warrior's Way (2010) with a massive budget of 425 Million Dollars!, followed by the Pirates of the Caribbean Duo with a budget of 368 and 315 Million Dollars respectively.
  • The top grossing movie is Avatar (2009) with a revenue of 2.83 Billion Dollars, followed by Star Wars and Titanic with a revenue of 2.79 and 2.51 Billion Dollars respectively.
  • The top profitable movie is Star Wars (1977) with a profit of 2.75 Billion Dollars, followed by Avatar and Titanic with a profit of 2.59 and 2.23 Billion Dollars respectively.

Q6: What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?

A quick reminder: To answer this question, we are working with the Data of the movies only with the highest revenues. (higher than the average)

1- Release Date:

  • Most of the top revenue movies are usually released on December, June and july.
  • A huge number of movies are usually released on Fridays, Thursdays and Wednesdays.

    Top Revenue movies are usually released on Fridays/ Thursday nights. By this it is easier for people to make time to see them during the weekend, also when Thursdays happen to be a holiday, some movies comes out on Wednesday for the same reason.

2- Genre, Director, Cast and Production Company:

  • The most involved Genre is Action, followed by Drama and Comedy.
  • The most involved Director is Seven Spielberg, followed by Robert Zemeckis.
  • The most involved Actor is Tom Cruise, followed by Tom Hanks and Brad Pitt.
  • The most involved Production company is Warner Bros*, followed by Universal Pictures and Paramount Pictures.

    The above information gives us some insights that some genres tends to attract more revenues than others, also the movie Director, Cast, and Production Company play a great role in the popularity and revenue of the movie as all these factors improves the movie quality.

3- Budget:

  • There is a positive relation between the movie Budget and its Revenue as higher spending in production phase (spending on the Best Directors, Actors and Production Companies) improves the movie quality which in turn leads to a higher revenue.

4- Popularity & Rating:

  • There is a positive relation between the movie Popularity and Rating and its Revenue as high popularity movies generate a buzz by a whole bunch of people going to the theater to see the movie so it draws more people to see the movie. Today, with social media, it's even more important to get as many people talking about a movie (good or bad) at once to populate the newsfeeds with reminders to go watch it, making it having high voting/rating counts Hince, getting higher Ratings which in turn leads to a higher revenue.

5- Runtime

  • There is a good relation between the movie Runtime and its Revenue. But generally longer movies does not necessarily mean higher revenues.

Limitations¶

There are some limitations in the Data that certainly impacted our Analysis which can be listed below:

1- The Budget and Revenue columns contain more than 50% zero values!.
2- The popularity column values are not clear; how it is calulated or what criteria it is based on.
3- The Cast, Director, Genres, and Specially the Production Companies columns contain a lot of missing values which can affect the Analysis.
4- The Data contains a lot of irrelevant columns with a lot of missing values such as Homepage, Tagline, Keywords and Overview columns.
5- Some columns of the Data contain outliers such as: Runtime, Budget and Revenue.
